ract","webTitle":"Extracts","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/extract","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/extract","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-04-04T11:29:48Z","webTitle":"Inside the mind Frank Cottrell Boyce via his scrapbook  – in pictures","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"gallery","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"childrens-books-site/gallery/2016/apr/04/frank-cottrell-boyce-scrapbook-sputniks-guide-to-life","fields":{"byline":"Frank Cottrell Boyce","headline":"Inside the mind Frank Cottrell Boyce via his scrapbook  – in pictures","trailText":"When Frank Cottrell Boyce has an idea for a book, the first thing he does is make a scrap book of all his ideas. Check out some fascinating pages from the one he made for his new book Sputnik’s Guide to Life on Earth","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"2a3b74dba5485d543f9798fc8c40590f8f304a56\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/2a3b74dba5485d543f9798fc8c40590f8f304a56/0_0_1000_1341/746.jpg\" alt=\"Sputnik scrapbook\" width=\"746\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Whenever I think I’ve got an idea I make up a scrapbook and send it to my editor, Sarah Dudman. She will always tell me straight what is exciting in there - and what isn’t. <br><br>In this gallery I’m sharing some of my favourite pages from the scrapbook I made when I was writing my latest book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/385665/\">Sputnik’s Guide to Life on Earth</a>, I hope you like it!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a94ac8bc08b68e0291d7155afd91d5b7bc6a5b84\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a94ac8bc08b68e0291d7155afd91d5b7bc6a5b84/0_0_1000_1339/747.jpg\" alt=\"Tesco traffic lights\" width=\"747\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">In case you can’t read my handwriting I’ve typed out the text too: People always ask where you get ideas from. In the case of Sputnik I can, for once, be pretty precise. The idea crashed into my car on the Formby Bypass, just after the Tesco traffic lights. My daughter was in the car, I said, “What about this – a boy answers the door to a stranger. The stranger comes in and the parents are really welcoming but odd. They keep telling the stranger he’s a clever boy or a pretty boy. The hero realises that everyone else sees the stranger as a dog.” She said: “That’ll work.”</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a0a34988b0c59e7997b98295290d8f95736f6754\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a0a34988b0c59e7997b98295290d8f95736f6754/0_0_1000_747/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Sputnik means companion\" width=\"1000\" height=\"747\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sputnik means “companion”. He should wear a kilt, a flying helmet and smoke a cigar. <br><br><a></a>I knew that Sputnik was a loud explosive character. I put <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VM-pV6wWnuQ\">this brilliant clip from YouTube</a> into the mix as a reminder of the unpredictable, firework feel I wanted him to have. <br><br>I also knew right away that he was from space!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9e7f29bc6e8690291b3a03e791c648ad2ab2f811\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9e7f29bc6e8690291b3a03e791c648ad2ab2f811/0_0_1000_747/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Laika\" width=\"1000\" height=\"747\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">As soon as the dog idea came into my head, I thought of Laika and the Soviet Space dogs. Laika is now thought to have died on take-off but what if she didn’t? What if she was found by aliens who assumed that she had built the rocket? What if they assumed dogs were Earth’s dominant species?<br><br>What if they ARE!?</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6f59bee3bbe72b2abbe8e3a3f45a84ddc2548e49\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/6f59bee3bbe72b2abbe8e3a3f45a84ddc2548e49/0_0_1000_1339/747.jpg\" alt=\"Toby Dog\" width=\"747\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">You should know I have no experience of dogs… I’ve never had a pet of any description. The only relationship I’ve had with a dog was in my late teens when I was a Punch an Judy man. The puppets and booth were made by my hero English teacher Mr Biggs. We had a “Toby Dog” – a dog in a ruff that took a hat round to collect the money. He used to sit up and beg in a very endearing manner. Until someone mugged him in George over Sands. The dog had a nervous breakdown and would beg no more…</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"923dd94dde5028b228d26e4e81c16f7d21be04be\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/923dd94dde5028b228d26e4e81c16f7d21be04be/0_0_3508_1318/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Steve Lenton\" width=\"1000\" height=\"376\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Steven Lenton had the difficult job of drawing Sputnik both as a dog and in his “human” form. <br>Steven says: “Once the alien version of Sputnik was complete translating this into the various canine iterations of the character came fairly easily. Because each human character sees him as a different breed this meant I didn’t have to worry too much about the dimensions of each dog and could instead focus mainly on their poses and expressions.”</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Steve Lenton</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"964c020262cffca5113098d04bb50bc4621c0076\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/964c020262cffca5113098d04bb50bc4621c0076/0_0_1000_1339/747.jpg\" alt=\"The Coo Palace\" width=\"747\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Coo Palace (Corseyard Model Dairy) is a massive gothic cow shed on a beach near Kirkcudbright. The minute I saw it, I wanted to buy it and live in it. When it was pointed out that it was MILES from everything, everyone I know and love, I said, “not by boat it wouldn’t be.” This convinced no one. <br> <br>The nearest I could get to owning it was by putting it in a book, so you’ll see more of Coo Palace in Sputnik’s Guide to Life.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"427c04a20d9d54c79f82683438b5dfacdddd48fe\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/427c04a20d9d54c79f82683438b5dfacdddd48fe/0_0_1000_1339/747.jpg\" alt=\"Esther\" width=\"747\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Contrast is always good so I thought the hero should be very quiet. I immediately thought of my niece Esther who is utterly charming and very capable but never utters a word in company. I’ve always been fascinated by people’s reaction to her. They are constantly trying to get her to talk. She’s a puzzle they feel they have to solve. By saying nothing she ends up dominating the conversation. That’s the power of quietness! I changed her to a boy and moved her from Ireland to Scotland.<br>Just to be clear that it’s not a story about Esther - just a story that owes her a big thank you…</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Frank Cottrell Boyce</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"5b6b52b4ff6047dadfdc222360cf64dcacbe5b5c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/5b6b52b4ff6047dadfdc222360cf64dcacbe5b5c/0_0_1631_2624/622.jpg\" alt=\"Sputnik's guide\" width=\"622\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/385665/\">Sputnik’s Guide to Life on Earth</a> by Frank Cottrell Boyce is out on 7 April 2016. You can read the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/ng-interactive/2016/apr/04/extract-sputniks-guide-to-life-on-earth-by-frank-cottrell-boyce-and-steve-lenton\">first chapter here</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/apr/04/frank-cottrell-boyce-sputnik-guide-to-life-on-earth-competition\">enter our competition to win a signed copy plus Sputnik goodies</a>.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Guardian Bookshop</span> </figcaption> </figure>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4t2zv","wordcount":"0","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/40189b3a52d7022dd61e4f275f932615876d3745/0_197_3504_2102/500.jpg","standfirst":"<p>When Frank Cottrell Boyce has an idea for a book, the first thing he does is make a scrap book of all his ideas. Check out some fascinating pages from the one he made for his new book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/385665/\">Sputnik’s Guide to Life on Earth </a></p><p>Read the first chapter of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/ng-interactive/2016/apr/04/extract-sputniks-guide-to-life-on-earth-by-frank-cottrell-boyce-and-steve-lenton\">Sputnik’s Guide to Life on Earth</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/apr/04/frank-cottrell-boyce-sputnik-guide-to-life-on-earth-competition\">Enter our Sputnik competition</a> and win signed copies plus Sputnik goodies! </p>"},"w