359a3599a973978d348c354840a5ab91b6\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/fb57d6359a3599a973978d348c354840a5ab91b6/0_0_649_501/649.jpg\" alt=\"The sun’s corona glowing in x-rays\" width=\"649\" height=\"501\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">There is more to the sun than meets the eye. This image shows the sun glowing with x-rays, a type of radiation that is absorbed by the Earth’s atmosphere. The sun emits light at all wavelengths across the electromagnetic spectrum, so the view from above the atmosphere is the only way to monitor the sun in all its glory. Space telescopes have become central to our ability to study the sun. They have revealed that the sun is a constantly evolving mass of plasma and tangled magnetic fields which is wracked by the most energetic explosions in the solar system</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Courtesy of Jaxa / National Astronomical Observatory of Japan / University of Tokyo / LMSAL</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"5f2f01cbedc5a0f36bf23f54afce88694ff2ced1\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/5f2f01cbedc5a0f36bf23f54afce88694ff2ced1/0_231_4096_3697/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Extreme ultraviolet image of the Sun showing a solar flare on the left side\" width=\"1000\" height=\"903\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Our sun is a magnetic object. The discovery of its magnetic field in 1908 marked the first time any such field had been detected beyond the Earth. It was a moment that changed our understanding of the sun. The magnetic field is the reason the sun has dark spots on its visible surface and an atmosphere at a temperature of about 1m°C (1.8m°F). It stores and releases energy that powers violent events like the solar flare seen on the left-hand side of this image</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Courtesy of Nasa / SDO and the AIA science team</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"38cd4aef1037dadec6148b04895682d863f601dc\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/38cd4aef1037dadec6148b04895682d863f601dc/0_0_2855_3000/952.jpg\" alt=\"Image of comet Hale-Bopp which was visible in 1997\" width=\"952\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">In the space age, we found that the sun is bigger than we had thought – much bigger. The first clue came from comets. As they approach the sun, comets release gas and dust in two tails which always point away from the sun. The dust tail is pushed outwards by the pressure of sunlight falling on the tiny particles, while the gas tail becomes electrically charged and is pushed outwards by the constant expansion of the sun’s atmosphere. Space probes have shown this atmosphere rushes out from the sun at high speeds, in a flow of charged particles known as the solar wind</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: ESO / E Slawik</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"62edb584648cbadd2e3355500dc4fb5480f9a1ab\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/62edb584648cbadd2e3355500dc4fb5480f9a1ab/0_42_1177_1248/943.jpg\" alt=\"A wireless operator typing a telegram\" width=\"943\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">On 2 September 1859, as stunning auroras lit up the skies, electric telegraph systems all over the world failed. Some operators found they could use their equipment without the need of batteries. Their systems were powered instead by a vast geomagnetic storm. The electric currents in the Earth’s atmosphere were caused by a coronal mass ejection from the sun that lifted off just as British amateur astronomer Richard Carrington observed the accompanying solar flare</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Bettmann / Corbis</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"44ad2b09ffd1ea78c9761632db9071a761117448\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/44ad2b09ffd1ea78c9761632db9071a761117448/0_0_1024_1024/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The ‘light bulb’ coronal mass ejections as seen by the Soho spacecraft\" width=\"1000\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Today the sun is seen as both friend and foe. Coronal mass ejections, such as the one shown in the top half of this image, can disrupt electrical grids, communication networks and transportation. We monitor the sun’s violent side using occulting disks which allow us to study the regions above the visible surface, marked here by the white circle. A coronal mass ejection on a collision course with the Earth sets space weather forecasters around the world springing into action to predict the likely consequences. We are all living in the sun’s atmosphere. And it can be a gusty and stormy place</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Courtesy of ESA / Nasa and the Lasco consortium</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"be8027c9da98e7450a745b3ebfb55bad23f9f2d9\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/be8027c9da98e7450a745b3ebfb55bad23f9f2d9/0_79_3500_2101/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Sunset over the Acropolis in Athens\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Our sun is a Goldilocks star. It’s not too hot and it’s not too cold, and it’s not particularly large or particularly small when compared to other stars in our galaxy. But it’s just big enough to keep burning for billions of years; long enough for complex and intelligent life to have formed, despite our sun’s capacity for violence. As our local star, we are able to observe it in unprecedented detail. But even though we have studied it for generations there are still fundamental questions left to answer</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Yannis Behrakis/Reuters</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c11c472ff36992d96ed33723859a41cb2197381a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/c11c472ff36992d96ed33723859a41cb2197381a/0_0_1630_2623/621.jpg\" alt=\"15 Million Degrees by Lucie Green (Viking)\" width=\"621\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/378250/\">15 Million Degrees </a>by Lucie Green is available from the Guardian bookshop</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Viking</span> </figcaption> </figure>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"Human beings have been studying the sun for thousands of years, but our nearest star has only recently begun to reveal its secrets. Lucie Green takes us on a journey to the heart of our local inferno","headline":"Staring at the sun: our local star – in pictures","byline":"Lucie Green"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2016/apr/04/the-sun-our-star-in-pictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/gallery/2016/apr/04/the-sun-our-star-in-pictures","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"0f0e5382d378cea23de99629dda46103781a5ecd","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0f0e5382d378cea23de99629dda46103781a5ecd/0_7_5159_3094/5159.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© Gary K Smith / Alamy","picdarUrn":"GD*25848668","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/0f0e5382d378cea23de99629dda46103781a5ecd","suppliersReference":"A1P2G0","altText":"A flock of geese takes off in front of the morning sun","caption":"One hundred and fifty million kilometres away, at the heart of our solar system, is the sun. Each sunrise illuminates us with light carrying the energy on which life relies. As the sun rises overhead, each square metre of the Earth’s surface is bombarded by 100bn photons every second – 