e 1990</p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2015/2/2/1422889931610/Robert-McCrum.jpg","bylineLargeImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2015/2/2/1422889948613/Robert-McCrum-L.png","firstName":"","lastName":"mccrum","r2ContributorId":"15288","rcsId":"GNL042186","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/robertmccrum","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/robertmccrum","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theobserver","sectionId":"theobserver","webTitle":"The Observer","type":"publication","description":"From the Observer, the Sunday newspaper and sister publication of the Guardian.","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theobserver","sectionName":"From the Observer","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"The New Review","type":"newspaper-book","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"newspaper-book-section","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-04-03T16:21:58Z","webTitle":"Life of Catherine Dickens to be celebrated in new exhibition","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/apr/03/life-of-catherine-charles-dickens-museum-exhibition-london-wife","fields":{"thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9/235_699_3265_1959/500.jpg","wordcount":"779","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4t3tq","standfirst":"<p>Installation at Charles Dickens Museum will overturn accepted narrative to show how wife of Victorian novelist was clever, affectionate and gifted at music</p>","body":"<p>The talents of Charles Dickens’s wife, who he separated from and portrayed as an unfit mother despite them having 10 children together, are to be celebrated in an exhibition at her former home in London.</p> <p>Catherine Dickens never made any public complaint about her husband’s treatment of her, which troubled even some of his closest friends. He first moved out of her bedroom and had the connecting door boarded shut, then formally separated from her, announcing in a newspaper advertisement in June 1858 that “some domestic trouble of mine of long standing” had been resolved.</p> <p>He insisted that the break – the exhibition will include the previously unseen lawyer’s draft of the deed of separation – “involves no anger or ill-will of any kind”, which was far from the truth. The woman he was really desperate to keep out of the public gaze was his much younger mistress, the actress <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/sep/07/ralph-fiennes-invisible-woman-charles-dickens\">Ellen Ternan</a>.</p> <p> The exhibition will open next month at the <a href=\"http://dickensmuseum.com/\">Charles Dickens Museum</a> in London, in the building that was the first house the couple rented together. It will be co-curated by Lillian Nayder, professor of English at Bates College in Maine. Nayder has published a <a href=\"http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100270960\">biography</a> of Catherine, rehabilitating her as a clever, affectionate woman, gifted at music, maintaining a circle of interesting friends after the separation, and devoted to her children despite Dickens characterising her as lacking any real feeling for them.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"71c8a3118fbb84d0cacc808fb78b765fbc7318f1\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/71c8a3118fbb84d0cacc808fb78b765fbc7318f1/0_515_6658_3996/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Interior of the Charles Dickens Museum at 48 Doughty Street\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Interior of the Charles Dickens Museum at 48 Doughty Street.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Siobhan Doran/siobhandoran.com</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“I think there is a recognition that her time has come,” Nayder said. “She has really been the ghost in the house in that museum, virtually written out of the story, even though it was her home too. I think with the first woman director and a woman curator at the museum it is a very different place, and they realise that the story of Catherine must also be acknowledged and told. </p> <p>“Dickens was such a powerful character, and his words carried such weight, that I think most scholars have just accepted it and chosen not to look closer at the real character of Catherine.”</p> <p>Nayder has even had her students try out some of the recipes Catherine published in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/dec/16/rereading-charles-dickens-dinner\">What Shall We Have for Dinner</a>, which less kind critics have taken as evidence of why she became so stout.</p> <p>“I think the break was a classic mid-life crisis,” she said. “He was remarkably youthful still, and she had had 10 children and several miscarriages. It was a terrible thing. Several of the men in their circle had quietly maintained mistresses, but forcing his wife out of her home was an extraordinary act which Charles then had to do everything to justify in public and maintain his own reputation. She never defended herself, never wrote or said a word against him in public.”</p> <p>When they met, and when they married less than two years later, in their early 20s, Charles was unknown and almost penniless. Catherine’s father, George Hogarth, was a newspaper editor who gave Charles one of his first breaks as a writer, commissioning stories that he wrote under the pen name Boz.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"9f570db11d95409f5e6437cbc707758a24b1415c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/9f570db11d95409f5e6437cbc707758a24b1415c/0_506_4243_2547/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Ring that belonged to Catherine Dickens\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Ring that belonged to Catherine Dickens.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Charles Dickens Museum collection</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The exhibition will be full of poignant reminders of the couple’s halcyon days, including a letter from her younger sister Mary within months of the marriage, describing Catherine as “a most capital housekeeper and as happy as the day is long”. The house at <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2012/jan/24/charles-dickens-interiors-in-pictures\">48 Doughty Street</a> was where two of their children were born. Mary died unexpectedly in Dickens’s arms, sending him into a spiral of grief. After the split, Catherine’s sister Georgina stayed with Dickens to the end of his life, looking after the children.</p> <p>The exhibition will also include the portrait and lock of his hair that he gave her on their engagement, with a ring set with turquoises – very like the one <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/23/why-charles-dickenss-best-character-is-non-existent\">David Copperfield</a> gives Dora – describing it as “a pretty little toy”. A small gilt coin purse, coming from a member of the Dickens family, is believed to be her wedding gift to him.</p> <p>A group of Catherine’s possessions resurfaced last year on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/28/antiques-roadshow-fa-cup-trophy-valued-at-more-than-1m\">Antiques Roadshow</a> and will be on display, on loan from their private owner, including a ring modelled as a gaping fanged serpent that she bequeathed to Georgina. <br /></p> <p>Nayder does not accept the legend that the hissing serpent was a last symbolic protest against her sister’s behaviour. “I think that’s another of the many myths about Catherine. I believe the twining snake was actually a Victorian symbol of friendship. She remained on good terms with Georgina, truly glad if she had been driven out of her home and could not be there, that Georgina was there almost as her surrogate, taking care of her family.” </p>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"Installation at Charles Dickens Museum will overturn accepted narrative to show how wife of Victorian novelist was clever, affectionate and gifted at music","headline":"Life of Catherine Dickens to be celebrated in new exhibition","byline":"Maev Kennedy"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/apr/03/life-of-catherine-charles-dickens-museum-exhibition-london-wife","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/apr/03/life-of-catherine-charles-dickens-museum-exhibition-london-wife","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9/235_699_3265_1959/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9","altText":"Detail from an engraving of Catherine Dickens","caption":"Detail from an engraving of Catherine Dickens. Charles sought to portray her as an unfit mother after their separation.","source":"Charles Dickens Museum collection","credit":"Photograph: Charles Dickens Museum collection","mediaId":"fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9/235_699_3265_1959/2000.jpg","width":"2000","height":"1200"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/fbc1c722791927750055e7ada4e6f758aefaf3e9/235_699_3265_1959/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://a